# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-active-directory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A domain controller is a server running the **Active Directory Domain Services** (**AD DS**) role.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It authenticates and authorizes all users and computers in a Windows domain-type network, assigning and enforcing security policies for all computers and installing or updating software.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] For example, when a user logs into a computer which is part of a Windows domain, Active Directory checks the submitted username and password and determines whether the user is a system administrator or a non-admin user.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory uses Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) versions 2 and 3, Microsoft's version of Kerberos, and DNS.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Like many information-technology efforts, Active Directory originated out of a democratization of design using Requests for Comments (RFCs).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) oversees the RFC process and has accepted numerous RFCs initiated by widespread participants.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] For example, LDAP underpins Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Also, X.500 directories and the Organizational Unit preceded the Active Directory concept that uses those methods.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The LDAP concept began to emerge even before the founding of Microsoft in April 1975, with RFCs as early as 1971.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] RFCs contributing to LDAP include RFC 1823 (on the LDAP API, August 1995), RFC 2307, RFC 3062, and RFC 4533.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft previewed Active Directory in 1999, released it first with Windows 2000 Server edition, and revised it to extend functionality and improve administration in Windows Server 2003.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory support was also added to Windows 95, Windows 98, and Windows NT 4.0 via patch, with some unsupported features.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Additional improvements came with subsequent versions of Windows Server.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] In Windows Server 2008, Microsoft added further services to Active Directory, such as Active Directory Federation Services.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The part of the directory in charge of managing domains, which was a core part of the operating system, was renamed Active Directory Domain Services (ADDS) and became a server role like others.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] "Active Directory" became the umbrella title of a broader range of directory-based services.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] According to Byron Hynes, everything related to identity was brought under Active Directory's banner.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Services consist of multiple directory services.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The best known is Active Directory Domain Services, commonly abbreviated as AD DS or simply AD.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) is the foundation of every Windows domain network.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It stores information about domain members, including devices and users, verifies their credentials, and defines their access rights.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The server running this service is called a domain controller.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A domain controller is contacted when a user logs into a device, accesses another device across the network, or runs a line-of-business Metro-style app sideloaded into a machine.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Other Active Directory services (excluding LDS, as described below) and most Microsoft server technologies rely on or use Domain Services; examples include Group Policy, Encrypting File System, BitLocker, Domain Name Services, Remote Desktop Services, Exchange Server, and SharePoint Server.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The self-managed Active Directory DS must be distinct from managed Azure AD DS, a cloud product.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services (AD LDS), previously called *Active Directory Application Mode* (ADAM), implements the LDAP protocol for AD DS.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It runs as a service on Windows Server and offers the same functionality as AD DS, including an equal API.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, AD LDS does not require the creation of domains or domain controllers.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It provides a Data Store for storing directory data and a *Directory Service* with an LDAP Directory Service Interface.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Unlike AD DS, multiple AD LDS instances can operate on the same server.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS) establishes an on-premises public key infrastructure.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It can create, validate, revoke and perform other similar actions, public key certificates for internal uses of an organization.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] These certificates can be used to encrypt files (when used with Encrypting File System), emails (per S/MIME standard), and network traffic (when used by virtual private networks, Transport Layer Security protocol or IPSec protocol).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] AD CS predates Windows Server 2008, but its name was simply Certificate Services.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory Federation Services (AD FS) is a single sign-on service.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] AD FS uses many popular open standards to pass token credentials such as SAML, OAuth or OpenID Connect.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] AD FS supports encryption and signing of SAML assertions.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] AD FS's purpose is an extension of that of AD DS: The latter enables users to authenticate with and use the devices that are part of the same network, using one set of credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The former enables them to use the same set of credentials in a different network.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] As the name suggests, AD FS works based on the concept of federated identity.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] AD FS requires an AD DS infrastructure, although its federation partner may not.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory is a service comprising a database and executable code.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It is responsible for managing requests and maintaining the database.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Directory System Agent is the executable part, a set of Windows services and processes that run on Windows 2000 and later.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Accessing the objects in Active Directory databases is possible through various interfaces such as LDAP, ADSI, messaging API, and Security Accounts Manager services.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory structures consist of information about objects classified into two categories: resources (such as printers) and security principals (which include user or computer accounts and groups).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Each security principal is assigned a unique security identifier (SID).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] An object represents a single entity, such as a user, computer, printer, or group, along with its attributes.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Some objects may even contain other objects within them.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Each object has a unique name, and its definition is a set of characteristics and information by a schema, which determines the storage in the Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Administrators can extend or modify the schema using the schema object when needed.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, because each schema object is integral to the definition of Active Directory objects, deactivating or changing them can fundamentally alter or disrupt a deployment.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Modifying the schema affects the entire system automatically, and new objects cannot be deleted, only deactivated.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Changing the schema usually requires planning.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] In an Active Directory network, the framework that holds objects has different levels: the forest, tree, and domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Domains within a deployment contain objects stored in a single replicable database, and the DNS name structure identifies their domains, the namespace.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A domain is a logical group of network objects such as computers, users, and devices that share the same Active Directory database.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] On the other hand, a tree is a collection of domains and domain trees in a contiguous namespace linked in a transitive trust hierarchy.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The forest is at the top of the structure, a collection of trees with a standard global catalog, directory schema, logical structure, and directory configuration.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The forest is a secure boundary that limits access to users, computers, groups, and other objects.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The objects held within a domain can be grouped into organizational units (OUs).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] OUs can provide hierarchy to a domain, ease its administration, and can resemble the organization's structure in managerial or geographical terms.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] OUs can contain other OUs—domains are containers in this sense.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft recommends using OUs rather than domains for structure and simplifying the implementation of policies and administration.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The OU is the recommended level at which to apply group policies, which are Active Directory objects formally named group policy objects (GPOs), although policies can also be applied to domains or sites (see below).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The OU is the level at which administrative powers are commonly delegated, but delegation can be performed on individual objects or attributes as well.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Organizational units do not each have a separate namespace.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] As a consequence, for compatibility with Legacy NetBios implementations, user accounts with an identical SamAccountName are not allowed within the same domain even if the accounts objects are in separate OUs.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] This is because SamAccountName, a user object attribute, must be unique within the domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, two users in different OUs can have the same common name (CN), the name under which they are stored in the directory itself such as "fred.staff-ou.domain" and "fred.student-ou.domain", where "staff-ou" and "student-ou" are the OUs.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Allowing for duplication of object names in the directory, or completely removing the use of NetBIOS names, would prevent backward compatibility with legacy software and equipment.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, disallowing duplicate object names in this way is a violation of the LDAP RFCs on which Active Directory is supposedly based.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] As the number of users in a domain increases, conventions such as "first initial, middle initial, last name" (Western order) or the reverse (Eastern order) fail for common family names like *Li* (李), *Smith* or *Garcia*.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Workarounds include adding a digit to the end of the username.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Alternatives include creating a separate ID system of unique employee/student ID numbers to use as account names in place of actual users' names and allowing users to nominate their preferred word sequence within an acceptable use policy.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] In Microsoft's Active Directory, OUs do not confer access permissions, and objects placed within OUs are not automatically assigned access privileges based on their containing OU.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It represents a design limitation specific to Active Directory, and other competing directories, such as Novell NDS, can set access privileges through object placement within an OU.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory requires a separate step for an administrator to assign an object in an OU as a group member also within that OU.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Using only the OU location to determine access permissions is unreliable since the entity might not have been assigned to the group object for that OU yet.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A common workaround for an Active Directory administrator is to write a custom PowerShell or Visual Basic script to automatically create and maintain a *user group* for each OU in their Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The scripts run periodically to update the group to match the OU's account membership.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, they cannot instantly update the security groups anytime the directory changes, as occurs in competing directories, as security is directly implemented into the Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Such groups are known as *shadow groups*.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Once created, these shadow groups are selectable in place of the OU in the administrative tools.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft's Server 2008 reference documentation mentions shadow groups but does not provide instructions on creating them.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Additionally, there are no available server methods or console snap-ins for managing these groups.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] An organization must determine the structure of its information infrastructure by dividing it into one or more domains and top-level OUs.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] This decision is critical and can base on various models such as business units, geographical locations, IT service, object type, or a combination of these models.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The immediate purpose of organizing OUs is to simplify administrative delegation and, secondarily, to apply group policies.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] While OUs serve as an administrative boundary, the forest itself is the only security boundary.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] All other domains must trust any administrator in the forest to maintain security.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Active Directory database is organized in *partitions*, each holding specific object types and following a particular replication pattern.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft often refers to these partitions as 'naming contexts'.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The 'Schema' partition defines object classes and attributes within the forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The 'Configuration' partition contains information on the physical structure and configuration of the forest (such as the site topology).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Both replicate all domains in the forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The 'Domain' partition holds all objects created in that domain and replicates only within it.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Some directory partitions store forest wide configuration information and schema information; other directory partitions store information specific to individual domains, such as users, groups, and organizational units.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Active Directory information is physically held on one or more peer domain controllers, replacing the NT PDC/BDC model.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Each DC has a copy of the Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Member servers joined to Active Directory that are not domain controllers are called Member Servers.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] In the domain partition, a group of objects acts as copies of domain controllers set up as global catalogs.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] These global catalog servers offer a comprehensive list of all objects in the forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Global Catalog servers replicate all objects from all domains to themselves, providing an international listing of entities in the forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, to minimize replication traffic and keep the GC's database small, only selected attributes of each object are replicated, called the *partial attribute set* (PAS).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The PAS can be modified by modifying the schema and marking features for replication to the GC.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Earlier versions of Windows used NetBIOS to communicate.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory is fully integrated with DNS and requires TCP/IP—DNS.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] To fully operate, the DNS server must support SRV resource records, also known as service records.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Active Directory uses multi-master replication to synchronize changes, meaning replicas pull changes from the server where the change occurred rather than being pushed to them.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Knowledge Consistency Checker (KCC) uses defined sites to manage traffic and create a replication topology of site links.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Intra-site replication occurs frequently and automatically due to change notifications, which prompt peers to begin a pull replication cycle.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Replication intervals between different sites are usually less consistent and don't usually use change notifications.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, it's possible to set it up to be the same as replication between locations on the same network if needed.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Each DS3, T1, and ISDN link can have a cost, and the KCC alters the site link topology accordingly.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Replication may occur transitively through several site links on same-protocol *site link bridges* if the price is low.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, KCC automatically costs a direct site-to-site link lower than transitive connections.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A bridgehead server in each zone can send updates to other DCs in the exact location to replicate changes between sites.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] To configure replication for Active Directory zones, activate DNS in the domain based on the site.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] To replicate Active Directory, Remote Procedure Calls (RPC) over IP (RPC/IP) are used.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] SMTP is used to replicate between sites but only for modifications in the Schema, Configuration, or Partial Attribute Set (Global Catalog) GCs.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It's not suitable for reproducing the default Domain partition.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Generally, a network utilizing Active Directory has more than one licensed Windows server computer.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Backup and restore of Active Directory are possible for a network with a single domain controller.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, Microsoft recommends more than one domain controller to provide automatic failover protection of the directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Domain controllers are ideally single-purpose for directory operations only and should not run any other software or role.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Since certain Microsoft products, like SQL Server and Exchange, can interfere with the operation of a domain controller, isolation of these products on additional Windows servers is advised.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Combining them can complicate the configuration and troubleshooting of the domain controller or the other installed software more complex.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] If planning to implement Active Directory, a business should purchase multiple Windows server licenses to have at least two separate domain controllers.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Administrators should consider additional domain controllers for performance or redundancy and individual servers for tasks like file storage, Exchange, and SQL Server since this will guarantee that all server roles are adequately supported.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] One way to lower the physical hardware costs is by using virtualization.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] However, for proper failover protection, Microsoft recommends not running multiple virtualized domain controllers on the same physical hardware.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The Active-Directory database, the *directory store*, in Windows 2000 Server uses the JET Blue-based Extensible Storage Engine (ESE98).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Each domain controller's database is limited to 16 terabytes and 2 billion objects (but only 1 billion security principals).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Microsoft has created NTDS databases with more than 2 billion objects.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] NT4's Security Account Manager could support up to 40,000 objects.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It has two main tables: the *data table* and the *link table*.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Windows Server 2003 added a third main table for security descriptor single instancing.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Programs may access the features of Active Directory via the COM interfaces provided by *Active Directory Service Interfaces*.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] To allow users in one domain to access resources in another, Active Directory uses trusts.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Trusts inside a forest are automatically created when domains are created.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The forest sets the default boundaries of trust, and implicit, transitive trust is automatic for all domains within a forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] One domain allows access to users on another domain, but the other domain does not allow access to users on the first domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Two domains allow access to users on both domains.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The domain that is trusted; whose users have access to the trusting domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A trust that can extend beyond two domains to other trusted domains in the forest.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] A one way trust that does not extend beyond two domains.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] It is not transitive and is one way only.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] An explicit trust between domains in different trees or the same tree when a descendant/ancestor (child/parent) relationship does not exist between the two domains.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Joins two domains in different trees, transitive, one- or two-way.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Can be transitive or nontransitive (intransitive), one- or two-way.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Connect to other forests or non-Active Directory domains.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] functionality level) 'bastion' forest, which issues time-limited group memberships.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] These management tools may not provide enough functionality for efficient workflow in large environments.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Some third-party tools extend the administration and management capabilities.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] They provide essential features for a more convenient administration process, such as automation, reports, integration with other services, etc.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The schema additions shipped with Windows Server 2003 R2 include attributes that map closely enough to RFC 2307 to be generally usable.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The reference implementation of RFC 2307, nss_ldap and pam_ldap provided by PADL.com, support these attributes directly.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The default schema for group membership complies with RFC 2307bis (proposed).
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Windows Server 2003 R2 includes a Microsoft Management Console snap-in that creates and edits the attributes.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] An alternative option is to use another directory service as non-Windows clients authenticate to this while Windows Clients authenticate to Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Non-Windows clients include 389 Directory Server (formerly Fedora Directory Server, FDS), ViewDS v7.2 XML Enabled Directory, and Sun Microsystems Sun Java System Directory Server.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] The latter two are both able to perform two-way synchronization with Active Directory and thus provide a "deflected" integration.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Another option is to use OpenLDAP with its *translucent* overlay, which can extend entries in any remote LDAP server with additional attributes stored in a local database.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Clients pointed at the local database see entries containing both the remote and local attributes, while the remote database remains completely untouched.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Administration (querying, modifying, and monitoring) of Active Directory can be achieved via many scripting languages, including PowerShell, VBScript, JScript/JavaScript, Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Free and non-free Active Directory administration tools can help to simplify and possibly automate Active Directory management tasks.
[src:azure-active-directory/active-directory] Since October 2017 Amazon AWS offers integration with Microsoft Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] In computing, a **directory service** or **name service** maps the names of network resources to their respective network addresses.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] It is a shared information infrastructure for locating, managing, administering and organizing everyday items and network resources, which can include volumes, folders, files, printers, users, groups, devices, telephone numbers and other objects.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] A directory service is a critical component of a network operating system.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] A **directory server** or name server is a server which provides such a service.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Each resource on the network is considered an object by the directory server.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Information about a particular resource is stored as a collection of attributes associated with that resource or object.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] A directory service defines a namespace for the network.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] The namespace is used to assign a *name* (unique identifier) to each of the objects.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Directories typically have a set of rules determining how network resources are named and identified, which usually includes a requirement that the identifiers be unique and unambiguous.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] When using a directory service, a user does not have to remember the physical address of a network resource; providing a name locates the resource.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Some directory services include access control provisions, limiting the availability of directory information to authorized users.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Several things distinguish a directory service from a relational database.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Attributes are sometimes multi-valued, allowing multiple naming attributes at one level (such as machine type and serial number concatenation, or multiple phone numbers for "work phone").
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Attributes and object classes are usually standardized throughout the industry; for example, X.500 attributes and classes are often formally registered with the IANA for their object ID.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Therefore, directory applications try to reuse standard classes and attributes to maximize the benefit of existing directory-server software.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Object instances are slotted into namespaces; each object class inherits from its parent object class (and ultimately from the root of the hierarchy), adding attributes to the must-may list.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Directory services are often central to the security design of an IT system and have a correspondingly-fine granularity of access control.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Replication and distribution have distinct meanings in the design and management of a directory service.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Replication is used to indicate that the same directory namespace (the same objects) are copied to another directory server for redundancy and throughput reasons; the replicated namespace is governed by the same authority.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Distribution is used to indicate that multiple directory servers in different namespaces are interconnected to form a distributed directory service; each namespace can be governed by a different authority.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Directory services were part of an Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) initiative for common network standards and multi-vendor interoperability.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] During the 1980s, the ITU and ISO created the X.500 set of standards for directory services, initially to support the requirements of inter-carrier electronic messaging and network-name lookup.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] The Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) is based on the X.500 directory-information services, using the TCP/IP stack and an X.500 Directory Access Protocol (DAP) string-encoding scheme on the Internet.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Open-source tools to create directory services include OpenLDAP, the Kerberos protocol and Samba software, which can function as a Windows domain controller with Kerberos and LDAP back ends.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Administration is by GOsa or Samba SWAT.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Name services on Unix systems are typically configured through nsswitch.conf.
[src:azure-active-directory/directory-service] Information from name services can be retrieved with getent.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:azure-active-directory/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Despite its name, LDAP is much more than its protocol (i.e., much more than its HTTP API); it includes specifications of the required operation of systems satisfying its HTTP API and even specifies a standardized model of the data to be used by the HTTP API and managed by the directory service.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory services play an important role in developing intranet and Internet applications by allowing the sharing of information about users, systems, networks, services, and applications throughout the network.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As examples, directory services may provide any organized set of records, often with a hierarchical structure, such as a corporate email directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, a telephone directory is a list of subscribers with an address and a phone number.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common use of LDAP is to provide a central place to store usernames and passwords.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This allows many different applications and services to connect to the LDAP server to validate users.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is a simpler (*lightweight*) subset of the standards in the X.500 series, particularly the X.511 Directory Access Protocol.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Because of this relationship, LDAP is sometimes called **X.500 Lite**.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Telecommunication companies' understanding of directory requirements were well developed after some 70 years of producing and managing telephone directories.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These companies introduced the concept of directory services to information technology and computer networking, their input culminating in the comprehensive X.500 specification, a suite of protocols produced by the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) in the 1980s.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] X.500 directory services were traditionally accessed via the X.511 Directory Access Protocol (DAP), which required the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) protocol stack.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP was originally intended to be a lightweight alternative protocol for accessing X.500 directory services through the simpler (and now widespread) TCP/IP protocol stack.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This model of directory access was borrowed from the DIXIE and Directory Assistance Service protocols.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The protocol was originally created by Tim Howes of the University of Michigan, Steve Kille of Isode Limited, Colin Robbins of Nexor and Wengyik Yeong of Performance Systems International, circa 1993, as a successor to DIXIE and DAS.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Mark Wahl of Critical Angle Inc., Tim Howes, and Steve Kille started work in 1996 on a new version of LDAP, LDAPv3, under the aegis of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPv3, first published in 1997, superseded LDAPv2 and added support for extensibility, integrated the Simple Authentication and Security Layer, and better aligned the protocol to the 1993 edition of X.500.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Further development of the LDAPv3 specifications themselves and of numerous extensions adding features to LDAPv3 has come through the IETF.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the early engineering stages of LDAP, it was known as *Lightweight Directory Browsing Protocol*, or *LDBP*.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was renamed with the expansion of the scope of the protocol beyond directory browsing and searching, to include directory update functions.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It was given its *Lightweight* name because it was not as network intensive as its DAP predecessor and thus was more easily implemented over the Internet due to its relatively modest bandwidth usage.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP has influenced subsequent Internet protocols, including later versions of X.500, XML Enabled Directory (XED), Directory Service Markup Language (DSML), Service Provisioning Markup Language (SPML), and the Service Location Protocol (SLP).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It is also used as the basis for Microsoft's Active Directory.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A client starts an LDAP session by connecting to an LDAP server, called a Directory System Agent (DSA), by default on TCP and UDP port 389, or on port 636 for LDAPS (LDAP over TLS/SSL, see below).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client then sends an operation request to the server, and a server sends responses in return.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] With some exceptions, the client does not need to wait for a response before sending the next request, and the server may send the responses in any order.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] All information is transmitted using Basic Encoding Rules (BER).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In addition the server may send "Unsolicited Notifications" that are not responses to any request, e.g. before the connection is timed out.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A common alternative method of securing LDAP communication is using an SSL tunnel.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The default port for LDAP over SSL is 636.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The use of LDAP over SSL was common in LDAP Version 2 (LDAPv2) but it was never standardized in any formal specification.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This usage has been deprecated along with LDAPv2, which was officially retired in 2003.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A DN may change over the lifetime of the entry, for instance, when entries are moved within a tree.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To reliably and unambiguously identify entries, a UUID might be provided in the set of the entry's *operational attributes*.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`dn`" is the distinguished name of the entry; it is neither an attribute nor a part of the entry.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] "`cn=John Doe`" is the entry's RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), and "`dc=example,dc=com`" is the DN of the parent entry, where "`dc`" denotes 'Domain Component'.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The other lines show the attributes in the entry.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attribute names are typically mnemonic strings, like "`cn`" for common name, "`dc`" for domain component, "`mail`" for email address, and "`sn`" for surname.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A server holds a subtree starting from a specific entry, e.g.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may also hold references to other servers, so an attempt to access "`ou=department,dc=example,dc=com`" could return a *referral* or *continuation reference* to a server that holds that part of the directory tree.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client can then contact the other server.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some servers also support *chaining*, which means the server contacts the other server and returns the results to the client.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP rarely defines any ordering: The server may return the values of an attribute, the attributes in an entry, and the entries found by a search operation in any order.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This follows from the formal definitions - an entry is defined as a set of attributes, and an attribute is a set of values, and sets need not be ordered.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The ADD operation inserts a new entry into the directory-server database.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the distinguished name in the add request already exists in the directory, then the server will not add a duplicate entry but will set the result code in the add result to decimal 68, "entryAlreadyExists".
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In the above example, `uid=user,ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must not exist, and `ou=people,dc=example,dc=com` must exist.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When an LDAP session is created, that is, when an LDAP client connects to the server, the **authentication state** of the session is set to anonymous.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The BIND operation establishes the authentication state for a session.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Simple BIND and SASL PLAIN can send the user's DN and password in plaintext, so the connections utilizing either Simple or SASL PLAIN should be encrypted using Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server typically checks the password against the `userPassword` attribute in the named entry.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Anonymous BIND (with empty DN and password) resets the connection to anonymous state.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] SASL (Simple Authentication and Security Layer) BIND provides authentication services through a wide range of mechanisms, e.g.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Kerberos or the client certificate sent with TLS.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND also sets the LDAP protocol version by sending a version number as an integer.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the client requests a version that the server does not support, the server must set the result code in the BIND response to the code for a protocol error.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Normally clients should use LDAPv3, which is the default in the protocol but not always in LDAP libraries.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] BIND had to be the first operation in a session in LDAPv2, but is not required as of LDAPv3.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] In LDAPv3, each successful BIND request changes the authentication state of the session and each unsuccessful BIND request resets the authentication state of the session.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an entry, an LDAP client transmits a properly formed delete request to the server.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Search operation is used to both search for and read entries.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name of the base object entry (or possibly the root) relative to which the search is to be performed.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] What elements below the baseObject to search.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] (the entire subtree starting at the base DN).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Criteria to use in selecting elements within scope.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] determine whether the values for those attributes match the filter assertion.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Note that a common misconception is that LDAP data is case-sensitive, whereas in fact matching rules and ordering rules determine matching, comparisons, and relative value relationships.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Which attributes to return in result entries.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Maximum number of entries to return, and maximum time to allow search to run.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These values, however, cannot override any restrictions the server places on size limit and time limit.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Return attribute types only, not attribute values.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server returns the matching entries and potentially continuation references.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The final result will include the result code.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Compare operation takes a DN, an attribute name and an attribute value, and checks if the named entry contains that attribute with that value.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation is used by LDAP clients to request that the LDAP server make changes to existing entries.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attempts to modify entries that do not exist will fail.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] MODIFY requests are subject to access controls as implemented by the server.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The MODIFY operation requires that the distinguished name (DN) of the entry be specified, and a sequence of changes.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To replace the value of an existing attribute, use the `replace` keyword.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to update.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] To delete an attribute from an entry, use the keyword `delete` and the changetype designator `modify`.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the attribute is multi-valued, the client must specify the value of the attribute to delete.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is also a Modify-Increment extension which allows an incrementable attribute value to be incremented by a specified amount.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] When LDAP servers are in a replicated topology, LDAP clients should consider using the post-read control to verify updates instead of a search after an update.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The post-read control is designed so that applications need not issue a search request after an update – it is bad form to retrieve an entry for the sole purpose of checking that an update worked because of the replication eventual consistency model.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP client should not assume that it connects to the same directory server for each request because architects may have placed load-balancers or LDAP proxies or both between LDAP clients and servers.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Modify DN (move/rename entry) takes the new RDN (Relative Distinguished Name), optionally the new parent's DN, and a flag that indicates whether to delete the value(s) in the entry that match the old RDN.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may support renaming of entire directory subtrees.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An update operation is atomic: Other operations will see either the new entry or the old one.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] On the other hand, LDAP does not define transactions of multiple operations: If you read an entry and then modify it, another client may have updated the entry in the meantime.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers may implement extensions that support this, though.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Extended Operation is a generic LDAP operation that can define new operations that were not part of the original protocol specification.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] StartTLS is one of the most significant extensions.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Other examples include Cancel and Password Modify.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The StartTLS operation establishes Transport Layer Security (the descendant of SSL) on the connection.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It can provide data confidentiality (to protect data from being observed by third parties) and/or data integrity protection (which protects the data from tampering).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] During TLS negotiation the server sends its X.509 certificate to prove its identity.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The client may also send a certificate to prove its identity.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] After doing so, the client may then use SASL/EXTERNAL.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] By using the SASL/EXTERNAL, the client requests the server derive its identity from credentials provided at a lower level (such as TLS).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Though technically the server may use any identity information established at any lower level, typically the server will use the identity information established by TLS.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Servers also often support the non-standard "LDAPS" ("Secure LDAP", commonly known as "LDAP over SSL") protocol on a separate port, by default 636.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAPS differs from LDAP in two ways: 1) upon connect, the client and server establish TLS before any LDAP messages are transferred (without a StartTLS operation) and 2) the LDAPS connection must be closed upon TLS closure.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some "LDAPS" client libraries only encrypt communication; they do not check the host name against the name in the supplied certificate.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Abandon operation requests that the server abort an operation named by a message ID.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Neither Abandon nor a successfully abandoned operation send a response.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A similar Cancel extended operation does send responses, but not all implementations support this.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The Unbind operation abandons any outstanding operations and closes the connection.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The name is of historical origin, and is *not* the opposite of the Bind operation.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients can abort a session by simply closing the connection, but they should use Unbind.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Unbind allows the server to gracefully close the connection and free resources that it would otherwise keep for some time until discovering the client had abandoned the connection.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] It also instructs the server to cancel operations that can be canceled, and to not send responses for operations that cannot be canceled.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Most of the components described below are optional.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As in other URLs, special characters must be percent-encoded.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] There is a similar non-standard `ldaps` URI scheme for LDAP over SSL.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This should not be confused with LDAP with TLS, which is achieved using the StartTLS operation using the standard `ldap` scheme.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The contents of the entries in a subtree are governed by a directory schema, a set of definitions and constraints concerning the structure of the directory information tree (DIT).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema of a Directory Server defines a set of rules that govern the kinds of information that the server can hold.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes are the elements responsible for storing information in a directory, and the schema defines the rules for which attributes may be used in an entry, the kinds of values that those attributes may have, and how clients may interact with those values.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Clients may learn about the schema elements that the server supports by retrieving an appropriate subschema subentry.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Each entry must have an objectClass attribute, containing named classes defined in the schema.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The schema definition of the classes of an entry defines what kind of object the entry may represent - e.g. a person, organization or domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The object class definitions also define the list of attributes that must contain values and the list of attributes which may contain values.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, an entry representing a person might belong to the classes "top" and "person".
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Membership in the "person" class would require the entry to contain the "sn" and "cn" attributes, and allow the entry also to contain "userPassword", "telephoneNumber", and other attributes.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Since entries may have multiple ObjectClasses values, each entry has a complex of optional and mandatory attribute sets formed from the union of the object classes it represents.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] ObjectClasses can be inherited, and a single entry can have multiple ObjectClasses values that define the available and required attributes of the entry itself.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A parallel to the schema of an objectClass is a class definition and an instance in Object-oriented programming, representing LDAP objectClass and LDAP entry, respectively.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Directory servers may publish the directory schema controlling an entry at a base DN given by the entry's subschemaSubentry operational attribute.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Server administrators can add additional schema entries in addition to the provided schema elements.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A schema for representing individual people within organizations is termed a white pages schema.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection is a computer security attack similar to SQL injection that can occur when an application implementing LDAP fails to properly sanitize user input.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As an example, consider an LDAP search query that allows the user to search people by their name, the `cn` attribute.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] A malicious user might replace a valid name with the `*` character, which matches any object with the `cn` attribute.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the application is vulnerable to this attack, it may display attributes that the searching user is not authorized to see.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP injection vulnerabilities are mitigated by escaping variables.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Escaping is accomplished with two distinct encoding functions — one for Distinguished Names and one for search strings — because they each allow different special characters.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Some web frameworks come with escaping built in.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Like other parts of TCP/IP, LDAP was originally created without encryption.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This makes it vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks, in which attackers intercept credentials during the bind process.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This attack can be mitigated by requiring LDAPS or StartTLS during every bind involving credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Much of the server operation is left to the implementor or administrator to decide.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Accordingly, servers may be set up to support a wide variety of scenarios.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, data storage in the server is not specified - the server may use flat files, databases, or just be a gateway to some other server.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Access control is not standardized, though there are commonly used models.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Users' passwords may be stored in their entries or elsewhere.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The server may refuse to perform operations when it wishes, and impose various limits.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Examples: One can define new operations.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] *Controls* may modify requests and responses, e.g. to request sorted search results.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] New search scopes and Bind methods can be defined.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Attributes can have *options* that may modify their semantics.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] As LDAP has gained momentum, vendors have provided it as an access protocol to other services.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The implementation then recasts the data to mimic the LDAP/X.500 model, but how closely this model is followed varies.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, there is software to access SQL databases through LDAP, even though LDAP does not readily lend itself to this.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Similarly, data previously held in other types of data stores are sometimes moved to LDAP directories.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, Unix user and group information can be stored in LDAP and accessed via PAM and NSS modules.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] LDAP is often used by other services for authentication and/or authorization (what actions a given already-authenticated user can do on what service).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] For example, in Active Directory Kerberos is used in the authentication step, while LDAP is used in the authorization step.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of such data model is the GLUE Schema, which is used in a distributed information system based on LDAP that enable users, applications and services to discover which services exist in a Grid infrastructure and further information about their structure and state.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An LDAP server may return referrals to other servers for requests that it cannot fulfill itself.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] This requires a naming structure for LDAP entries so one can find a server holding a given distinguished name (DN), a concept defined in the X.500 Directory and also used in LDAP.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Another way of locating LDAP servers for an organization is a DNS server record (SRV).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An organization with the domain example.org may use the top level LDAP DN `dc=example, dc=org` (where *dc* means domain component).
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] If the LDAP server is also named ldap.example.org, the organization's top level LDAP URL becomes `ldap://ldap.example.org/dc=example,dc=org`.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] Primarily two common styles of naming are used in both X.500 [2008] and LDAPv3.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] These are documented in the ITU specifications and IETF RFCs.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The original form takes the top level object as the country object, such as `c=US`, `c=FR`.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] The domain component model uses the model described above.
[src:azure-active-directory/lightweight-directory-access-protocol] An example of country based naming could be `l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, c=FR`, or in the US: `cn=Common Name, l=Locality, ou=Some Organizational Unit, o=Some Organization, st=CA, c=US`.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider performs a security check on behalf of the target resource.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] If a valid security context at the service provider already exists, skip steps 2–7.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] If the user does not have a valid security context, the identity provider identifies the user (details omitted).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The assertion consumer service processes the response, creates a security context at the service provider and redirects the user agent to the target resource.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Since a security context exists, the service provider returns the resource to the user agent.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:azure-active-directory/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:azure-active-directory/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
